---
import PageLayout from '../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
---

<PageLayout name="Chu spaces" back wide description="Finite Chu spaces, duality, separation, extensionality, and Chu morphisms.">
  <section class="chu-hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">points × states → values</p>
    <h1>Chu spaces</h1>
    <p>
      A Chu space is a rectangular table of observations. Its rows are <strong>points</strong>, its columns are
      <strong>states</strong> or tests, and each cell records a value in a fixed set <code>K</code>. This tiny
      format carries a surprising amount of structure: duality is matrix transposition, and maps are pairs of
      functions that preserve every observation.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="chu-panel" id="chu-app">
    <div class="chu-controls">
      <label>
        space
        <select id="chu-space-select">
          <option value="sierpinski" selected>Sierpiński open-set tester</option>
          <option value="powerset">subsets versus membership</option>
          <option value="preorder">three-point preorder</option>
          <option value="ratings">objects rated by observers</option>
        </select>
      </label>
      <label>
        view
        <select id="chu-view-select">
          <option value="space" selected>space</option>
          <option value="dual">dual</option>
        </select>
      </label>
    </div>

    <div class="chu-summary" id="chu-summary"></div>

    <div class="chu-grid">
      <article class="chu-card chu-wide">
        <h2>evaluation matrix</h2>
        <div class="chu-table-wrap" id="chu-matrix"></div>
      </article>

      <article class="chu-card">
        <h2>separation diagnostics</h2>
        <div id="chu-diagnostics"></div>
      </article>

      <article class="chu-card">
        <h2>orthogonality profile</h2>
        <div id="chu-profile"></div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="chu-panel">
    <h2>morphism finder</h2>
    <p class="chu-muted">
      A morphism <code>(f,g): (A,r,X) → (B,s,Y)</code> uses a point map <code>f: A → B</code> and a
      backwards state map <code>g: Y → X</code>. The adjointness condition is
      <code>s(f(a), y) = r(a, g(y))</code> for every point <code>a</code> and state <code>y</code>.
    </p>
    <div class="chu-controls">
      <label>
        source C
        <select id="chu-source-select"></select>
      </label>
      <label>
        target D
        <select id="chu-target-select"></select>
      </label>
    </div>
    <div class="chu-morphism-output" id="chu-morphism-output"></div>
  </section>

  <section class="chu-columns">
    <article>
      <h2>definition</h2>
      <p>
        Fix a set <code>K</code> of truth values, colors, scores, or observations. A Chu space over <code>K</code>
        is a triple <code>(A, r, X)</code> where <code>A</code> is a set of points, <code>X</code> is a set of states,
        and <code>r: A × X → K</code> is the evaluation map.
      </p>
      <p class="chu-formula"><code>a ⊥ x = r(a,x)</code></p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h2>dual</h2>
      <p>
        The dual space swaps rows and columns: <code>(A,r,X)* = (X, rᵀ, A)</code>. In the dual, old states
        become points and old points become states. Applying duality twice gets back the original space.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="chu-columns">
    <article>
      <h2>separated and extensional</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Separated:</strong> no two points have the same row.</li>
        <li><strong>Extensional:</strong> no two states have the same column.</li>
        <li><strong>Biextensional collapse:</strong> identify equal rows and equal columns to remove observational duplicates.</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h2>why they matter</h2>
      <p>
        Chu spaces give a symmetric language for objects and predicates. They appear in categorical logic,
        linear logic, formal concept analysis, topology, automata, and models where systems are understood by
        the tests they pass and the observations they produce.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>
</PageLayout>

<style>
  .chu-hero { margin-bottom: calc(var(--space) * 1.2); }
  .chu-hero h1 { max-width: none; }
  .chu-hero p:not(.eyebrow), .chu-muted, .chu-card li, .chu-card p, .chu-columns p, .chu-columns li { color: var(--muted); }
  .chu-hero p:not(.eyebrow) { max-width: 58rem; }
  .chu-panel, .chu-card, .chu-columns article { border: 1px solid var(--line); padding: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
  .chu-panel { display: grid; gap: 1rem; }
  .chu-controls { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 1rem; align-items: end; }
  .chu-controls label { display: grid; gap: .25rem; color: var(--muted); }
  .chu-controls select { min-width: 16rem; background: var(--bg); color: var(--fg); border: 1px solid var(--line); border-radius: 4px; padding: .35rem .45rem; font: inherit; }
  .chu-summary, .chu-morphism-output { border: 1px solid var(--line); padding: 1rem; color: var(--muted); }
  .chu-grid, .chu-columns { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(min(100%, 22rem), 1fr)); gap: 1rem; }
  .chu-wide { grid-column: 1 / -1; }
  .chu-card { margin-bottom: 0; }
  .chu-card h2, .chu-panel h2, .chu-columns h2 { font-size: 1rem; margin-bottom: .6rem; }
  .chu-table-wrap { overflow-x: auto; }
  .chu-table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; min-width: max-content; font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums; }
  .chu-table th, .chu-table td { border: 1px solid var(--line); padding: .4rem .55rem; text-align: center; }
  .chu-table th { color: var(--fg); font-weight: 600; }
  .chu-list { display: grid; gap: .35rem; margin: 0; padding-left: 1.25rem; }
  .chu-chip { display: inline-block; border: 1px solid var(--line); border-radius: 999px; padding: .05rem .45rem; margin: .1rem; white-space: nowrap; color: var(--fg); }
  .chu-formula { color: var(--fg) !important; }
</style>

<script>
  import '../scripts/chu-spaces.ts';
</script>
